Graph Databases (GDBs) are essential for managing large-scale interconnected data. While GDB-backed Graph Neural Network (GNN) pipelines are feasible, their performance often lag behind in-memory implementations due to I/O bottlenecks and significant data transfer.
However, in comparison to in-memory stores, our GDB solution drastically cut costs due to the decreased amount of RAM needed and makes training possible on resource-constrained machines.
This thesis establishes the functional equivalence between GDB-resident sampling techniques and standard in-memory approaches, then identifies critical architectural bottlenecks. By pushing computation directly into the database engine, we minimize data movement during training. Furthermore, we introduce a novel approach of in-database inference, co-locating data with procedures for GNN-forward passes and sampling. The thesis benchmarks across diverse datasets to reveal how graph characteristics such as node-degree distribution, graph size, and feature dimensionality, impacts the efficacy of these optimizations. -w
